# File Organization – Per-Item Directories

- **Goal**: Keep related implementation, test, and support files together in their own directory, instead of mixing many `*.ts` / `*.spec.ts` files flat in a single folder.

## Rule

- **When a logical item has multiple files** (for example `foo.util.ts` and `foo.util.spec.ts`, or a component + spec + styles), those files **must live in their own directory named after the item**, not flat alongside other items.
- The parent folder (e.g. `core/`, `events/`, `teams/`) should contain **one subdirectory per item/feature**, not many sibling `*.ts` + `*.spec.ts` files.
- This applies across the repo for:
  - Angular utilities, services, components, and feature pieces.
  - NestJS modules, controllers, services, and helpers.
  - Any other TypeScript code where implementation and tests (and optionally styles/templates) belong together.

## Examples

**Do – per-item directory**

- `apps/ui/src/app/core/error-mapping/error-mapping.ts`
- `apps/ui/src/app/core/error-mapping/error-mapping.spec.ts`

**Don’t – flat mixing of many items**

- `apps/ui/src/app/core/error-mapping.ts`
- `apps/ui/src/app/core/error-mapping.spec.ts`
- `apps/ui/src/app/core/filter-validation.ts`
- `apps/ui/src/app/core/filter-validation.spec.ts`

## Additional Notes

- When an item later gains more files (e.g. `foo.ts` → adds `foo.spec.ts`, `foo.types.ts`), **move it into its own directory at that point**.
- Keep the directory name aligned with the item/feature name; avoid generic folders like `utils/` inside `core/` that reintroduce flat `*.ts` + `*.spec.ts` clutter.

